Guide: Choosing Your IDE (Maxpri Engineering)
1. Overview
Maxpri engineers need an IDE that supports Git, extensions, debugging, and efficient development workflows. While you may use any editor you prefer, the recommended choice is Visual Studio Code (VS Code) because it integrates directly with Git and provides a full-featured development environment.

Recommended IDE: Visual Studio Code
Why VS Code is Highly Recommended
VS Code offers the features required for Maxpri’s engineering workflow:

Built‑in Git support

Full Git UI (commit, push, pull, branch management)

Integrated terminal

Extensions for every major language and framework

Debugging tools

Workspace organization

Support for SSH development and remote containers

Reliable performance across Windows, macOS, and Linux

Git Integration
VS Code allows you to use Git directly inside the editor:

View changes

Stage and commit

Push and pull

Manage branches

Resolve merge conflicts

View Git history

This is essential because Maxpri uses Git for all source control, and VS Code makes the workflow straightforward.

If you check the Git folder in your onboarding materials, you’ll see examples and instructions that align directly with VS Code’s Git interface.

Alternative Option: Web‑Based IDEs
You may use a web IDE if necessary, but be aware of the limitations:

Limitations of Web IDEs
Very limited feature set

No built‑in Git support

No local debugging

No extensions

No integrated terminal

Often slower and less reliable

Not suitable for long‑term Maxpri development work

Web IDEs are acceptable only for quick edits or emergency access. They are not recommended for daily engineering tasks.
